{"tid":1453441,"cid":5,"subCid":0,"title":"[商討] 快！聲援俄羅斯兄弟！","createTime":"2019-08-12T04:13:08.000Z","updateTime":"2019-08-13T02:28:04.000Z","uid":160564,"like":167,"dislike":13,"uniUserReply":68,"replies":[{"pid":"72b2704a106839d6ca9dfd166db1e347ea9d3895","tid":1453441,"uid":160564,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":2,"replyTime":"2019-08-12T04:13:08.000Z","msg":"有見俄羅斯時下局勢同香港相似，係到我想係到拋磚引玉，商討同俄羅斯反對派合作嘅可能性。我先交待背景，然後提供支持理據，最後建議可行方法。<br />\n<br />\n背景：<span style=\"font-size: medium;\"> <span style=\"color: red;\"><strong>普京政府DQ反對派參選莫斯科市政府選舉，又拘捕反對絕大部份派領袖，引起群眾不滿，繼而引發於多個城市人民上街遊行示威。</strong></span></span>遊行已持續一個月。<strong><span style=\"color: red;\"><span style=\"font-size: medium;\">最近俄羅斯警察使用過分暴力對付示威者</span></span></strong>，例如有一位女士被5個警員帶走嘅時候係無構成威脅嘅情況下被一個警員打佢個肚。<span style=\"color: red;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: x-large;\">即使有2千人被捕，反而令更多人上街反對普京政府同警察</span></strong></span>。最近一次係莫斯科嘅遊行有6萬人參加，為7年黎最多。<br />\n<br />\n<strong>點解要幫俄羅斯反對派？</strong><br />\n1 同病相憐，當地社會廣泛支持示威，同時好多都係年輕人做上街抗議骨幹，<strong><span style=\"color: red;\">有先決條件一齊合作</span></strong><br />\n2 <strong><span style=\"color: red;\">理念相近</span></strong>：認同民主、反對極權管治。兄弟爬山各自努力，應互相扶持<br />\n3 <strong><span style=\"font-size: medium;\"><span style=\"color: red;\">如果不久將來反對派成功上台，普京落台，一方面增加我方國際聲望,甚至實質上嘅支持(戰鬥民族最勁係咩?）</span></span></strong>，令一方面支國會少左一個盟友，變相<strong><span style=\"color: red;\">增加我方籌碼。</span></strong><br />\n4 有助<strong><span style=\"color: red;\">促進港俄交流</span></strong>，或有利增加本地經濟貿易活動，認識俄仔俄妹不是夢<br />\n<br />\n<strong><span style=\"color: red;\">可行方法：</span></strong><br />\n1 聲援集會／遊行，同時譴責香港政府<br />\n2 到俄國駐港大使館請願<br />\n3 網上連儂牆<br />\n<br />\n<strong><span style=\"font-size: large;\"><span style=\"color: red;\">當打通溝通渠道後，或可以進行戰略上交流，甚至協調，增加國際上輿論壓力畀兩地政府。</span></span></strong><br />\n<br />\n<strong>各位兄弟如認同請幫手推同埋畀意見</strong><br />\n反應正面嘅話就take action!<br />\n<br />\n背景source: Financial Time <br />\n<br />\n<strong>Tens of thousands join Moscow protest rally Arrest of opposition leaders and heavy police presence fail to deter protesters </strong> (節錄)<br />\n<br />\nRussia&rsquo;s opposition staged its <strong>largest rally in several years</strong> as tens of thousands of people took to the streets in defiance of miserable weather on Saturday, underscoring the Kremlin&rsquo;s difficulties in stemming a month of pro-democracy protests. <br />\n<br />\nAbout 60,000 people attended the gathering on Moscow&rsquo;s Sakharov Avenue to<strong><span style=\"color: red;\"> protest against a Kremlin decision to bar opposition candidates from running for Moscow city council,</span></strong> according to the White Counter, an independent monitoring group. <br />\n<br />\nPolice claimed 20,000 had attended the rally, which was approved by the authorities, but under heavy guard. <br />\nDespite concerted efforts to quash it, including the arrest of <strong><span style=\"font-size: x-large;\"><span style=\"color: red;\">more than 2,400 people at previous protests and the jailing of nearly all the opposition&rsquo;s leaders, the rally showed that the desire to protest is growing stronger amid popular anger at president Vladimir Putin</span></span></strong>.<br />\n<br />\n<strong>His approval ratings are at their lowest level on record due to discontent over falling living standards.</strong><br />\n<br />\nThough the city council election is relatively inconsequential,<strong><span style=\"font-size: xx-large;\"><span style=\"color: red;\"> violent attacks by riot police on overwhelmingly peaceful protesters have galvanised people dissatisfied with Mr Putin&rsquo;s rule</span></span></strong>.<br />\n<br />\nOne video that went viral showed a policeman punching a young female protester in the stomach on Saturday as five officers led her away. <br />\n<br />\nPolina Urikh, 16, said she had decided to join the weekend protest because riot police broke her friend&rsquo;s fingers as they arrested her a week ago. <br />\n<br />\n<strong>&ldquo;I&rsquo;d be ashamed to stay behind,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;We should have changed everything [years ago], but since that didn&rsquo;t work out, we&rsquo;ll do it now. Maybe there&rsquo;ll be a revolution &mdash; that would be the coolest thing.&rdquo; </strong><br />\n<br />\nIn another sign that the protest movement is spreading, <strong>solidarity rallies were held in several cities across Russia,</strong> despite provincial Russians&rsquo; long-held disdain for wealthy Moscow. Police arrested 79 people in St Petersburg as well as 13 in Rostov-na-Donu and two each in the sleepy towns of Bryansk and Syktyvkar"},{"pid":"cae13296b50d7b8537c8369ab266c56d86df3b7d","tid":1453441,"uid":24133,"like":4,"dislike":33,"score":-29,"citedBy":4,"replyTime":"2019-08-12T04:14:28.000Z","msg":"<img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/surprise.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" />"},{"pid":"cf89876fbcb092f4e698307064ca882c87d8a582","tid":1453441,"uid":24133,"like":2,"dislike":12,"score":-10,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2019-08-12T04:14:28.000Z","msg":"<img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/surprise.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" />"},{"pid":"22f97230ef80557a033ee91816a1dd6ceb4a698a","tid":1453441,"uid":160564,"like":0,"dislike":0,"score":0,"citedBy":0,"replyTime":"2019-08-12T04:15:13.000Z","msg":"push"},{"pid":"8ddbb0b58c15c63d202cf4b51aaac0d8be859a62","tid":1453441,"uid":160564,"like":45,"dislike":0,"score":45,"quote":{"pid":"cae13296b50d7b8537c8369ab266c56d86df3b7d","tid":1453441,"uid":24133,"like":4,"dislike":33,"score":-29,"citedBy":4,"replyTime":"2019-08-12T04:14:28.000Z","msg":"<img src=\"/assets/faces/normal/surprise.gif\" class=\"hkgmoji\" />"},"citedBy":1,"replyTime":"2019-08-12T04:16:10.000Z","msg":"反對極權，追求民主嘅都係朋友!!"},{"pid":"ab9871d0ea966f72e163ac75e2adcfa86b85699d","tid":1453441,"uid":24133,"like":1,"dislike":16,"score":-15,"quote":{"pid":"8ddbb0b58c15c63d202cf4b51aaac0d8be859a62","tid":1453441,"uid":160564,"like":45,"dislike":0,"score":45,"quote":{"pid":"cae13296b50d7b8537c8369ab266c56d86df3b7d","tid":1453441,"uid":24133,"like":4,"dislike":33,"score